Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Until the laboratory results are available, it is not possible to
determine the cause of these encephalitis cases. There are several
alphaviruses and flaviviruses in Argentina that could cause
encephalitis in the burros. However, failure to find possible mosquito
vectors does argue against arthropod-borne viruses. It is extremely
difficult to isolate infectious virus from brain tissue from animals
dead from arthropod-borne equine encephalitis viruses, but PCR
detection of viral RNA may be successful.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of
Rivadavia department in San Juan province can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/1tqE. - Mod.TY]

[The authorities are clearly worried about one of the equine
encephalitides. They took the precaution of spraying the area and
closing the park. Closing the park may not solve the problem as
vectors can travel many miles at a time, especially carried by wind.
If the authorities are concerned about Eastern equine encephalitis
(EEE), then owners should be instructed to vaccinate their animals.
EEE is transmitted by mosquitoes from birds to the person. It does not
normally transmit from mammals to humans.

The concern of the virus entering people and causing fatalities makes
me think this virus could be the Venezuelan equine encephalopathy
(VEE).

People should be reminded to use insect repellant and to wear long
sleeves. There are mosquito and fly repellant available for equines
and owners should be encouraged to use them. - http://mod.tg/ -
Mod.TG]

